<dl id="n08066l"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n08" href="#n08066l">N08 (VI.B.6)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n08all.htm#n08066l"> 66(l)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ~ man called Sheffeld ~ <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n08066l"> <li>FW unlocated</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Caxton &hellip; gives us a graphic description of the struggle between the native <i>ey</i> and the Scandinavian <i>egg</i>: And certaynly our langage now used varyeth ferre from that whiche was used and spoken whan I was borne. For we englysshe men ben borne under the domynacyon of the mone, whiche is never stedfaste &hellip;. And that comyn englysshe that is spoken in one shyre varyeth from a nother. In so moche that in my dayes happened that certayn marchauntes were in a shippe in tamyse, for to have sayled over the see into zelande. &hellip; And one of theym named sheffelde &hellip;, cam in-to an hows and axed for mete; and specyally he axyd after eggys. &hellip; Loo, what sholde a man in thyse dayes now wryte, egges or eyren. Certaynly it is harde to playse every man, by cause of dyversite &amp; chaunge of langage. <small> Otto Jespersen, <a name="OJGS" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#OJGS"><cite title="source">The Growth and Structure of the English Language</cite></a>, 4th ed. (Jul 1923) 67</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: See also: <a name="n06129q" href="n06all.htm#n06129q">N06 (VI.B.11):129(q)</a> </mm> </dd></dl>
